ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to research scientists at the United States Department of
Agriculture Agricultural Research Service, Lane, OK, Fusarium wilt severely
limits production of watermelon. There are 3 races worldwide. Cultivars
with no resistance genes are affected by race 0. Highly resistant
cultivars, in conjunction with crop rotation, provide good control of race
1, the predominant race in most watermelon production areas. There is no
acceptable level of resistance to race 2 in commercial watermelon
cultivars. Seedless watermelon cultivars are generally very susceptible to
Fusarium wilt. Increased emphasis on seedless watermelon production is
likely to result in Fusarium wilt becoming a limiting disease in that crop.
An additional general reference can be obtained at:
<http://www.extento.hawaii.edu/kbase/Crop/Type/f_oxy2.htm> - Mod.DH
